<TEXT>
alexander khalifman a 24yearold from 
leningrad won the 1990 new york open chess tournament tuesday 
taking the 20000 first prize 
khalifman playing in his first tournament in the united states 
was the only player among 63 entrants in the prestigious 
international section to score 7 points in the nineround event 
the field included 32 grandmasters the highest title holders in 
chess short of world champion and 21 international masters who 
are one level below grandmaster eleven countries were represented 
in the competition at the penta hotel where players competed for a 
total purse of 48600 
khalifman an international master clinched first place by 
defeating 21yearold grandmaster ferdinand hellers of sweden in a 
46move game 
he sacrificed a pawn but it was a very unclear sacrifice 
khalifman said following their fivehour game i made some good 
moves and my chances became better and better 
gata kamsky 15 of new york who defected here from the soviet 
union with his father during last years new york open was among 
four players who finished half a point behind khalifman in a tie 
for second place kamsky earned 4825 as did grandmaster helgi 
olafsson of iceland and leningrad international masters leonid 
yudasin and vladimir epishin who also finished with 6 points 
apiece 
competitors earn one point for each win and onehalf point for 
each draw 
their results were good enough to earn khalifman kamsky 
yudasin and epishin each an international grandmaster norm one 
of the qualifying results necessary to be awarded the grandmaster 
title 
khalifman will be one of the players representing the soviet 
union in junes interzonal tournament in madrid the first 
qualification event for the 1993 world championship 
he said he hoped to be granted the grandmaster title by fide 
the international chess federation next month and thought the 
title was overdue i already have four gm grandmaster results 
i am ready to become a grandmaster 
it normally takes three norms to qualify for the title 
international master patrick wolff of belmont mass also 
earned a grandmaster norm wolff finished in a tie for sixth place 
with grandmasters joel benjamin of new york and smbat lputian of 
armenia each finished the tournament with 6 points and earned 
1033 
former world champion mikhail tal of riga latvia earned 5 
points and finished in a tie with 10 others for ninth place each 
won 518 
in mondays penultimate round kamsky defeated tal in 45 moves 
tal who was competing in his first new york tournament held the 
world title in 196061 
former world champion anatoly karpov who will be challenging 
world champion garri kasparov in new york for the world title in 
october dropped by during the fourth round of the international 
competition 
a total of 710 players competed for an overall purse of 150000 
in six sections of varying playing strengths in the open now in 
its eighth year the tournament began april 8 
</TEXT>
