<TEXT>
colombias top generals said one of the 
worlds most powerful cocaine cartels is being torn apart in a 
dispute over its use of violence to intimidate the government 
on tuesday the chief of the countrys secret police gen 
miguel maza said some of the cartels leaders are opposed to the 
organizations campaign of killings and bombings in the belief that 
the violence is making the government more resolute in its fight 
against the drug trade 
president virgilio barco ordered a government crackdown on the 
traffickers in august 
in response the leader of the medellin cocaine cartel pablo 
escobar ordered a campaign of bombings and assassinations that has 
claimed more than 200 lives 
since beginning its crackdown the government has extradited 15 
traffickers to the united states and its security forces have 
seized millions of dollars in traffickers property and raided 
several cocaine labs 
one of the cartels leaders gonzalo rodriguez gacha was killed 
in a shootout with police in december since then police and army 
officials have said they are close to capturing the four remaining 
leaders of the cartel 
now security officials say internal pressures are causing the 
cartel to fall apart 
on sunday a statement purportedly issued by cartel dissidents 
said some traffickers oppose escobars use of violence 
there was widespread skepticism in colombia over the 
communiques authenticity colombias traffickers have for years 
used violence as a tool in building and maintaining their cocaine 
empire 
