the value of tobacco exports doubled in the 
1980s contributing nearly 25 billion to the us trade account 
during the decade according to an industry report 
the study released tuesday by the tobacco merchants association 
of the united states said exports increased to almost 5 billion 
in 1989 from 25 billion in 1980 
last year alone while us industry as a whole produced a 
merchandise trade deficit of about 109 billion the us tobacco 
industry contributed 42 billion to the positive side of the 
nations trade ledger the association said 
the association in its 75th year said it represents all 
sectors of the tobacco industry including growers manufacturers 
suppliers dealers distributors securities firms and management 
consultants 
farrell delman president of the association said the growth of 
tobacco exports since 1985 when they were valued at 215 billion 
is attributable to the opening up of key asian cigarette 
markets as well as sustained exports to the middle east and 
europe 
tobacco exports have come under fire from some us health 
authorities and others who contend it is wrong to push sales 
overseas when americans are being advised to quit smoking because 
of health risks 
before he retired last oct 1 thensurgeon general c everett 
koop told congress it was the height of hypocrisy to export 
tobacco koop had conducted a vigorous antismoking campaign 
while in office 
