the fact that i came back and among the circumstances that i 
did somehow just makes my whole justified kiraly said the 
predominant sentiment in my heart is im proud to be hungarian 
thirtyfour years ago when kiraly slipped into austria the 
revolution had failed and the soviets were hot on his trail there 
was no thought of returning 
the former brigadier general had spent years on death row for 
treason before communist leaders paroled him and others as part of 
a futile attempt to defuse growing popular outrage he joined the 
revolt shortly after it broke out oct 23 1956 
as the head of the national guard of freedom fighters kiraly 
was high on the list of men wanted by the postrevolutionary 
hungarian government staying would have meant the gallows as it 
did for premier imre nagy defense minister pal maleter and other 
leaders of the uprising 
their execution in 1958 shocked the western world kiraly then 
made a vow that seemed to make his exile permanent 
i set the precondition not to cross the frontier of this state 
until and unless my friends who became martyrs received the 
proper acknowledgement and honor in hungary 
kiraly was invited back to hungary on june 17 to speak at a 
reburial ceremony for his friends 
the hungarian communist leadership had been the only one in 
eastern europe to reject its monopoly on power without massive 
popular pressure 
in the process it embraced the 1956 revolution as legitimate 
rehabilitated the leaders of the uprising and moved their remains 
from weedrankled unmarked plots to proper graves 
as ranking communist officials stood with heads bowed kiraly 
invoked hungarys glorious day hundreds of thousands listened 
to his words some sobbing in catharsis 
for kiraly it ranked as one of the most memorable moments in a 
remarkable life along with his election to parliament in his home 
town of kaposvar about 90 miles southwest of budapest 
but not all the good times were in hungary 
kiraly said he felt an nearunparalled sense of accomplishment 
in 1964 when the students of the city university of new york 
elected him teacher of the year he speaks glowingly of the united 
states 
it was a very generous land i never felt any sense of 
confrontation there between being a decent american citizen and 
remaining a hungarian he said america will never be a closed 
book for me 
kiralys most vivid memories are still firmly rooted in 1956 
hungary and his face assumes a faraway look as he talks about the 
heady days of near victory and the despair of defeat and selfexile 
nothing compares to the election as head of the freedom 
fighter forces he said and those days will remain indelibly 
etched in my mind forever 
</TEXT>
