<TEXT>
american indian peyoteeaters say ritual 
use of the psychedelic cactus is unlikely to stop despite a us 
supreme court ruling that religious beliefs are no excuse for using 
illegal drugs 
the court tuesday upheld the decision of oregon officials who 
denied unemployment benefits to two drug counselors fired for 
eating peyote as part of their religious practices 
justice antonin scalia writing for the courts 63 majority 
said it would be courting anarchy to let a few do what is 
illegal for everyone else 
dissenting justices said the ruling permits religious oppression 
of indians a view supported by american indian spiritual leaders 
we have been doing this all these years before the 
constitution was here i dont see why we cant continue said 
emerson jackson president of the native american church of north 
america the umbrella group claims at least 250000 members 
belonging to 70 church chapters that practice the peyote ritual in 
23 western states 
