were fired after breaking a policy of adapt the nonprofit 
rehabilitation organization they worked for in douglas county 
ore by eating small amounts of peyote as part of a native 
american church sacrament smith is an american indian black is 
not but belongs to the church 
the two were fired in 198384 and denied unemployment benefits 
they did not use peyote on the job 
oregon officials see the case as a drugabuse issue 
we have always insisted the state is not required to pay 
people for using illegal substances no matter what their religious 
beliefs might be said oregon attorney general dave frohnmayer 
the court said our law does not discriminate against religions 
but defenders of peyote rituals see the case as a clash of 
cultures 
the native american church is the most persecuted bona fide 
religion in the united states said steven moore attorney for 
the native american rights fund in boulder colo the irony is 
that its one of the first its been here for 10000 years 
the small buttonshaped cactus contains mescaline a mild 
hallucinogen it grows mainly in the deserts of mexico and southern 
texas 
archaelogical evidence indicates the plant was used by indians 
10000 years ago said omer stewart a retired university of 
colorado anthropologist and author of the book peyote religion 
today the psychedelic cactus is dried into chewy strips ground 
into powder or made into a bitter tea its not likely to attract a 
wide following of casual users said stewart who has studied the 
ritual use of peyote since 1937 
jackson a navajo peyote priest from window rock ariz 
calls the peyoteinduced hallucinations teachings from the holy 
spirit he likens peyote to the sacramental wine used in roman 
catholic communion except that alcohol is habitforming and 
peyote is not 
he travels around the west as a road man administering 
peyote in fireside rituals of chanting and drumming that last all 
night 
the rituals build cultural ties and reduce the alcoholism that 
plagues indian reservations said ralph metzner academic vice 
president of the california institute of integral studies in san 
francisco and author of the psychedelic experience 
peyote also serves healing and psychotherapeutic roles metzner 
said in our more segmented approach we have doctors counselors 
and priests they have peyote 
congress repeatedly rejected attempts to ban the ritual use of 
peyote 
jackson is confident that peyote use will continue his concern 
for now is finding enough peyote which the church buys in texas 
from dealers regulated by state and federal governments 
were getting more members jackson said and the supplies 
are going down 
