<TEXT>
the supreme court ruled today that a federal 
judge may not personally raise property taxes to pay for school 
desegregation but can order school officials to do so 
by a 90 vote the court said us district judge russell g 
clark abused his discretion when he personally imposed a school 
district tax hike in kansas city mo 
but in a victory for civil rights forces the court upheld most 
of the steps clark ordered school officials to take to racially 
desegregate the schools 
in a 54 vote the court said the judge could order officials to 
raise taxes to pay for the ordered desegregation remedies and could 
instruct them to ignore state laws limiting the anount of school 
taxes 
writing for the court justice byron white used sweeping 
language that could affect schooldesegregation cases nationwide 
a local government with taxing authority may be ordered to 
levy taxes in excess of the limit set by state statute where there 
is reason based in the constitution for not observing the statutory 
limitation white wrote 
chief justice william h rehnquist and justices anthony m 
kennedy sandra day oconnor and antonin scalia dissented decrying 
the courts casual embrace of taxation imposed by the unelected 
lifetenured federal judiciary 
clark went too far the court said today local officials 
should at least have the opportunity to devise their own solutions 
to these problems white wrote 
whites opinion was joined by justices william j brennan 
thurgood marshall harry a blackmun and john paul stevens 
through the last three decades the court has given federal 
judges sweeping power to take whatever steps necessary to end 
racial segregation in public schools those steps have included the 
forced busing of students teacher reassignments and even the 
partial merger of separate school districts 
but the court in january split 54 in limiting federal judges 
power to stamp out civil rights violations as it overturned fines 
against yonkers ny councilmen who blocked a housing 
desegregation plan 
the court said the judge who imposed the fines had exceeded his 
authority and should have waited to see whether potentially 
bankrupting penalties against the city would force adoption of the 
desegregation plan 
in arguments before the justices last october on the kansas city 
case missouri lawyer h barton farr iii representing the state 
called a tax increase ordered by an unelected judge taxation 
without representation 
when it comes to federal courts farr said then there is no 
power to tax period 
todays decision rejected that argument 
before 1954 missouri law required schools to be racially 
segregated in the following 35 years the percentage of black 
students in kansas citys school district rose from 225 to about 
75 percent 
black parents sued in 1977 over the decline of what had become 
predominantly black schools alleging that black students were 
being denied equal educational opportunities 
clark ruled in 1987 that the school districts physical 
facilities have literally rotted and ordered state and district 
officials to upgrade them 
the 8th us circuit court of appeals upheld most of clarks 
order saying there are still vestiges of the dual school system 
lingering in the city school district and the district and the 
state have not met their obligations to disestablish that system 
the judges orders called for two major remedies 
a magnet school plan by the 199192 school year in which 
every high school and middle school and about half the elementary 
schools in the district will feature distinctive themes such as 
foreign languages performing arts or math and science 
a capital improvements program costing some 260 million to be 
completed by next fall 
the state was ordered to pay threefourths of the remedial 
costs the school district onefourth 
school district voters had rejected six proposals since 1970 to 
increase taxes for education clark nearly doubled the local 
property tax ordering the school district to raise the tax from 
205 to 4 per 100 of assessed valuation to help finance the 
capital improvements 
the court must weigh the constitutional rights of the 
taxpayers against the constitutional rights of black students in 
this case clark said the balance is clearly in favor of the 
students who are helpless without the aid of this court 
the 8th circuit court upheld the tax hike in 1988 today the 
nations highest court struck down the specific tax hike ordered 
but left open the option of some tax hike being imposed by the 
school district under court order 
the case is missouri vs jenkins 8811150 
