<TEXT>
the aids virus was found in almost one in 3000 
teens who applied for the military over a 42month period with the 
infection rate about equal among young women and men researchers 
reported today 
the data presented in this study suggest that hiv is a real 
and immediate threat to teenagers throughout the united states 
the researchers from the walter reed army institute of research in 
washington dc wrote in todays journal of the american medical 
association 
the study looked at 1141164 teens applying to enlist in the 
us military between october 1985 and march 1989 all of whom were 
tested for the human immunodeficiency virus which causes aids of 
that number 393 were hiv positive 
overall 48 of 150043 female applicants tested positive or 
032 percent and 345 of 991455 males or 035 percent the 
researchers said 
but women aged 17 and 18 tested positive more often than their 
male counterparts 28 of 102576 women or 027 percent compared 
with 177 of 763872 men or 023 percent an unusual phenomenon 
among any age group for example the malefemale ratio among 
adults with fullblown aids is 931 the researchers said 
the probable explanation the researchers said is that females 
aged 17 and 18 are more likely to have older infected sexual 
partners than males 
the study found that results varied widely in different regions 
with the most populous states accounting proportionately for the 
highest number of infected teen applicants 
hiv prevalence was greatest among minorities from densely 
populated counties the study said 
fiftytwo of the 90821 teens who tried to enlist in california 
tested hiv positive followed by 45 of 62244 in new york and 38 of 
73789 in texas nine states alaska colorado maine montana 
north dakota new hampshire rhode island south dakota and wyoming 
had no hivpositive applicants the study said 
the researchers reported that the prevalance of hiv infection 
among teen applicants appeared to decrease over the study period 
but cautioned that more research is needed to verify that finding 
they urged greater educational efforts to stop the spread of hiv 
and aids 
the virus that causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome 
damages the bodys immune system leaving victims susceptible to 
infections and cancer 
it is spread most often through sexual contact needles or 
syringes shared by drug abusers infected blood or blood products 
and from pregnant women to their offspring 
