<TEXT>
the supreme court ruled today that a lawyer 
who wins a civil rights case can collect a big chunk of a clients 
award under an agreement made when the attorney was hired 
by a 90 vote the court ruled against a california man awarded 
212 million and then ordered to pay 40 percent of the judgment to 
his lawyer 
justice byron r white writing for the court said federal 
civil rights law permits such contingentfee arrangements 
the case stems from a federal lawsuit by juan francisco venegas 
against long beach police officers venegas won a suit in which he 
said his murder conviction was based on perjured evidence 
venegas hired michael mitchell to represent him in the suit and 
agreed to pay the lawyer 40 percent of any award he won 
a federal court also awarded mitchell 75000 in legal fees a 
sum to be paid by the police officers 
mitchell and venegas parted ways in 1986 when the lawyer asked 
for an additional 10 percent of the judgment to represent venegas 
on appeal and venegas refused 
the lawyer then filed a court motion to place a lien on the 
judgment to recover his 40 percent fee or 406000 
a federal judge gave mitchell a partial victory ruling he may 
be entitled to the contingent fee but leaving the matter to a state 
court to decide 
mitchell won a bigger victory before the 9th us circuit court 
of appeals 
the appeals court last year sent the case back to the federal 
judge to reconsider the lawyers bid to enforce a lien on the 212 
million award 
today the supreme court agreed with the 9th circuit court that 
under federal civil rights law mitchell is not limited to 
courtawarded attorneys fees when there is a contingency fee 
agreement with a client 
the case is venegas vs mitchell 881725 
</TEXT>
