april 15 
grand forks nd herald on the legacy of the vietnam war 
the vietnam war put a tarnish on our national nobility 
american policymakers couldnt convince americans that the war was 
right and the rest of the world was equally doubtful the 
foundation of american moral leadership was cracked and it hasnt 
been completely repaired 
then there were the thousands who first found political power 
through opposition to the war the civil rights movement had shown 
the way and the free speech movement had trained new cadres 
but it was the war that energized so many young people that 
brought them into the streets and later into the political process 
this politicization would have happened in any case but the war 
made it happen in a particular way and that way has had a profound 
influence on how todays world works 
the years of that war the longest war in american history 
were years that molded the nation we dont know yet just how 
the war is a part of the nations unfinished business the 
divisiveness the bitterness the doubt the grief these all 
remain it is understanding and acceptance that still elude us 
perhaps the longing for them in the nations soul is as great 
as the grief in the nations heart and the doubt in the nations 
mind 
