<TEXT>
ultraviolet light treatment that is widely used to 
clear up psoriasis can dramatically increase the risk of rare 
genital cancer in men a study has found 
those who get high doses of the treatment known as puva face 
300 times the usual risk of squamous cell cancer of the penis and 
scrotum 
the research suggests that men exposed to any source of 
ultraviolet light including tanning booths should protect their 
genitals from the rays 
puva short for psoralen and ultraviolet a has been used 
since the early 1970s to treat severe psoriasis patients take 
pills that are activated inside their bodies by exposure to intense 
ultraviolet a 
while the treatment is highly effective it increases the risk 
of skin cancer the latest study suggests that mens genitals are 
especially susceptible to this unwanted side effect 
the increased risk makes it prudent for men to use genital 
protection whenever they are exposed to puva or other forms of 
ultraviolet radiation for therapeutic recreational or cosmetic 
reasons the researchers wrote 
they noted that tens of thousands of americans receive puva or 
ultraviolet b therapy for treatment of skin disease and more than 
1 million get ultraviolet radiation from tanning devices 
the study directed by dr robert s stern of bostons beth 
israel hospital was published in thursdays new england journal of 
medicine 
the doctors based their conclusions on a 12year follow up of 
892 men who received puva for psoriasis that typically covered 
onethird of their bodies fourteen of the men or just under 2 
percent developed genital cancers among those with high puva 
exposure 6 percent got this kind of cancer 
the men were five to 15 times more likely to develop cancers on 
their genitals than on other parts of their bodies 
because patients stand during therapy mens genitals are 
exposed to the light rays but womens are not only one cancer of 
the external genitals occurred among 488 women in the study 
dr john h epstein of the university of california san 
francisco said the results indicated that the male genitalia 
should be completely protected during puva and ultraviolet b 
therapy if they are not involved with psoriasis and they should 
receive a reduced dose if they are 
</TEXT>
