a study supports the widely held belief that poor 
patients are more expensive for hospitals to treat than are more 
affluent people 
although earlier research has come to conflicting conclusions on 
the point the medicare program already pays more to hospitals that 
take care of large numbers of poor people 
in a study published in thursdays new england journal of 
medicine doctors reviewed the cases of 16908 people admitted to 
five massachusetts hospitals in 1987 
poor patients remained hospitalized 3 percent to 30 percent 
longer than betteroff patients depending on the hospital and 
their bills were 1 percent to 18 percent higher 
the researchers said their work suggests that all hospitals 
not just those with large numbers should get extra payments for 
their poor patients 
the medicare program pays flat fees for specific illnesses but 
it does not give hospitals more money if patients are unusually 
sick and need longer stays 
the study was directed by dr arnold m epstein of brigham and 
womens hospital in boston the researchers did not attempt to 
learn why the poor needed to stay in the hospital longer 
