president bush today challenged critics who 
deride him for emphasizing additional research over immediate steps 
against global warming stating that we have never considered 
research a substitute for action 
speaking at the close of an international conference on climate 
change bush acknowledged criticism of his researchoriented 
approach and his emphasis on the need to assess economic factors 
to those who suggest were only trying to balance economic 
growth and environmental protection i say they miss the point 
bush told delegates many of whom have criticized his goslow 
approach 
we are calling for an entirely new way of thinking to achieve 
both while compromising neither by applying the power of the 
marketplace in the service of the environment he said 
above all bush told the government representatives the 
climate change debate is not about research versus action for we 
have never considered research a substitute for action 
bush said the united states has offered four proposals a 
charter for cooperation in science and economics research on global 
change possible creation of an international institutes for 
research on the science and economics of global change an 
international system for exchanging data and a statement of 
principles for international cooperation in scientific and 
economics research on global change 
i call on you to support these suggestions bush told the 
foreign delegates gathered for the conference 
 
