republics as well as lithuania 
an economic blockade would influence latvia estonia and the 
kaliningrad region of russia landsbergis was quoted as telling a 
news conference 
that would resemble an angry man beating himself eduardas 
potasinskas of lithuanian tv quoted landsbergis as saying 
but anticipating a possible soviet embargo the supreme council 
urged lithuanian factories and consumers to prepare themselves 
for spiritual endurance and strict economy on all consumption it 
did not annouce specific conservation measures 
at the end of two days of sometimes heated debate the supreme 
council drafted a letter to gorbachev promising that if talks began 
before may 1 it would not pass any more measures to implement its 
march 11 declaration of independence 
that offer represented an effort to compromise with moscow but 
was unlikely to be accepted by the soviet leadership 
in their resolution titled on the expansion of relations 
between the republic of lithuania and the ussr members of 
the supreme council reaffirmed their declaration of independence 
and also appealed to gorbachev not to use violence against 
lithuanians or impose the economic sanctions he threatened on 
friday 
gorbachev said that unless lithuania rolled back several laws 
supporting the declaration of independence he would impose an 
embargo on key supplies to the baltic republic of 38 million 
residents 
he did not spell out what materials would be cut off saying 
only that they would be those goods the soviet union sells abroad 
for hard currency meaning oil and natural gas 
lithuania is entirely dependent upon the soviet union for all 
its oil and gas and petroleum products are the soviet unions most 
profitable export 
lithuanias energy minister leonas asmantas said wednesday 
that oil and gas were being delivered as usual 
the day before asmantas reported receiving unofficial 
information that crude oil supplies and natural gas would be 
reduced wednesday in addition lithuanian gas officials said they 
received a telegram from a regional soviet energy official stating 
that supplies of natural gas would be curtailed sharply on the 
orders of the government 
lithuanian tv reported that residents saw soviet troops in 
several armored vehicles stopped wednesday morning near a pumping 
station at the mazheikiai refinery in the northwestern part of the 
republic but there was no interruption of service potasinskas 
said the presence of soldiers at the site was unusual he added 
sales of gasoline to lithuanian motorists have tripled this week 
as residents reacted to gorbachevs threat with panicbuying but 
stocks were adequate and no rationing was anticipated asmantas 
said 
gorbachevs 48hour deadline passed sunday night amid the 
threeday easter holiday in the heavily roman catholic republic 
the supreme council did not convene until tuesday although 
landsbergis and other leaders held an emergency meeting monday to 
assess the impact of an economic embargo 
it was the latest in a series of ultimatums gorbachev has issued 
since lithuanians declared their independence in most cases such 
as a demand that they surrender their private firearms he has not 
reacted when they refused to give in 
in addition to the threats the kremlin has sent tanks and 
military vehicles through lithuanias capital vilnius rounded up 
lithuanins who deserted from the red army seized buildings and 
barred western journalists from lithuania 
in washington secretary of state james a baker iii said action 
by moscow against lithuania could doom commercial relations between 
the soviet union and the united states 
its very difficult to see some of the commercial aspects of 
our relationship surviving the use of force or coercion against 
lithuania baker said 
in a separate letter to gorbachev the lithuanian legislature 
expressed regrets on the position and methods chosen by the 
ussr 
on our part as earlier we are prepared to discuss any 
issues taking into consideration all justified interests of the 
soviet union foremost those of its citizens and those of a 
strategic nature the letter said 
legislators said they were forming a delegation led by bronius 
kuzmickas vice president of the supreme council to travel to 
moscow for possible talks a previous delegation met with gorbachev 
adviser alexander n yakovlev but made no headway toward settling 
the dispute 
lithuania picked up support wednesday from neighboring poland 
with the solidarity delegation to the polish parliament adopting a 
resolution expressing concern over the growing pressure being 
exerted by moscow 
the delegation also suggesting that warsaw assist in 
negotiations between the republic and the kremlin 
