<TEXT>
a chemotherapy combination that includes a 
drug used to deworm farm animals was endorsed wednesday by a panel 
of experts as a standard treatment after patients in a late stage 
of colon cancer undergo surgery 
twelve cancer specialist assembled by the national institutes of 
health recommended that all physicians offer the drug combination 
of 5fluorouracil or 5fu and levamisole to patients who have 
been surgically treated for stage iii colon cancer 
the recommendation in effect endorses as standard treatment a 
chemotherapy that was tested in a national institute of cancer 
clinical trial that ended in october 
that national trial among 1300 patients found that 5fu and 
levamisole reduced death and cancer recurrence by up to a third 
levamisole is a drug widely used to remove worms from the 
intestinal tract of cows horses goats sheep and even elephants 
5fu is a standard cancer drug that has been used for about 30 
years 
the battle has not been won in colorectal cancer said dr 
glenn d steele jr a harvard professor who chaired the panel of 
specialists 
many many answers still need to come in before we are even 
close to winning the battle once someone is diagnosed with colon or 
rectal cancer 
one of the unanswered questions he said is how exactly 
levamisole works to reduce the recurrence of colon cancer the 
precise action of the drug in cancer treatment is not known 
its a little disquieting to not understand why it works 
said committee member dr david p winchester a chicago physician 
and a director of the american college of surgeons 
but steele said the consensus panel said it felt there was 
enough clinical evidence to merit recommending the combination for 
stage iii colon cancer 
the panel also recommended that surgery alone be used to treat 
patients in stage i of the disease suggesting the use of both 
chemotherapy and radiation for stages ii and iii of rectal cancer 
the experts also called for more clinical drug trials to better 
define treatment combinations for patients at all disease stages 
after surgery 
postsurgical therapy for colorectal cancer patients has been an 
area of intense study among physicians worldwide for decades but 
clincial drug trials have failed until recent years to show the 
additional treatment to be of any benefit 
because of poor results and severe toxic reactions to some 
chemotherapies many patients are treated only with surgery for 
late stage patients the cancer almost invariably returns 
colon and rectal cancer is the third leading cause of cancer 
death in the united states there are more than 150000 new 
colorectal cancers diagnosed annually 
of the new cases the panel said about 55000 colon cancer 
patients and 20000 rectal cancer patients are defined as high 
risk about half of that high risk group will die within five years 
in its report the committee said that 5fu and levamisole 
appears to reduce the risk of cancer recurrence by 41 percent and 
lower the overall death rate by 33 percent 
overal survival percentages at 3 years were estimated to be 
71 percent vs 55 percent for the control group the report said 
the control group received no chemotherapy 
side effects from 5fu and levamisole the committee said 
were well tolerated 
the panel said it found that patients at stage i of colon cancer 
had a survival rate of 80 percent to 90 percent after five years 
with surgery alone thus the experts said postsurgical therapy 
for this early stage of the disease was not recommended 
levamisole is available for human consumption in the united 
states only from the national institute of cancer the nci started 
providing the drug free to the physicians of stage iii colon cancer 
patients in october after ending the national trial of the drug 
the drug manufactured by a belgium company is expected to be 
available for general prescriptions this summer said nci spokesman 
dr mike hamilton he said the delay is caused by a manufacturing 
problem with packaging 
steele said the consensus panel recommended that physicians 
adopt a standard scale for evaluating the stages of colorectal 
cancer 
the scale uses the size and spread of the primary tumor the 
involvement of lymph nodes and the presence of metastasis or 
spread to distant organs to classify the disease stage the scale 
ranges from stage zero to stage iv 
</TEXT>
