<TEXT>
the soviet union has a significantly 
decreased capability of winning a conventional war against nato 
because of moscows eroding confidence in its warsaw pact allies 
the joint chiefs of staffs said wednesday 
the chiefs in their first international threat assessment since 
the berlin wall was opened in november said the likelihood of a 
conventional war escalating into a nuclear one continues to 
decline 
the annual study prepared by gen colin powell the chairman of 
the joint chiefs is supposed to present a big picture for the 
military in planning defense strategies and budgets 
congress was given a classified version of the report last month 
the report comes amid calls from lawmakers for sharp cuts in 
pentagon spending in light of reduced superpower tensions and 
repeated warnings from defense secretary dick cheney that caution 
should be used as fiscal constraints force changes in the nations 
defenses 
the study expresses a restrained sense of optimism about the 
revolutionary changes that have swept across eastern europe and the 
soviet union 
a dramatically different security environment is emerging that 
is principally characterized by a diminished soviet threat reduced 
defense resources and an increasingly complex world the study 
stated these realities imply a reshaping of us security 
policy strategy force posture and capabilities 
but the study also tempers such observations with warnings that 
the united states must be wary and ready in case soviet reforms 
are reversed or us security interests are challenged by threats 
from other sources such as drugs terrorism regional conflicts or 
third world nations armed with ballistic missiles 
the challenge is to reconcile enduring objectives and tasks 
with repostured and restructured forces without foreclosing options 
for hedging against new or renewed threats concluded the study 
which is formally titled the joint military net assessment 
the report says that while the transformation of domestic and 
foreign soviet policies is incomplete and may be reversible 
there is a broad agreement that the soviet leadership has decided 
to reverse a 20year pattern of growth in military spending and 
force posture 
the study notes that while the soviet union and the warsaw pact 
have significant force advantages unilateral force reductions 
and political change in eastern europe are eroding the soviets 
capability to conduct successful sustained conventional operations 
against nato additionally their confidence in the reliability of 
nonsoviet warsaw pact forces is diminished 
thus the study states the soviets have to consider the 
prospect that they would have to conduct a theater offensive 
against nato primarily on their own consequently their 
capability to accomplish theater strategic objectives is 
significantly decreased 
in the unlikely event that such a war did occur the potential 
for termination of such a conflict on terms favorable to the united 
states is much improved the study said 
it also said that the probability that nato would need to 
resort to the use of nonstrategic nuclear forces is assessed to 
decrease as conventionalforce reductions produce a better 
balance between the armies of eastern and western europe 
but the foundation of the us strategy of deterrence remains 
its triad of nuclear weapons the study said 
investment in a ballistic missile defense system is needed as 
a minimum to counter the possibility of a soviet missile attack 
against the united states and the potential caused by the 
proliferation of advanced missile systems among third world 
nations the report said 
yet in the same paragraph the study added in any case the 
risk of nuclear deterrence failing is assessed to be low and at 
this moment to be decreasing 
</TEXT>
