<TEXT>
after being plagued for years by a shortage of 
controllers chicagos air traffic control center has enough 
people but members of the controllers union said wednesday theres 
another problem not enough chairs 
during one shift last week at the chicago air route traffic 
control center in suburban aurora one controller sat on a wooden 
box because no more chairs were available said union chapter 
chairman jim poole 
the center handles more than 2 million planes a year including 
crosscountry flights and flights into and out of ohare 
international the nations busiest airport 
the lack of chairs poses no danger to air safety and no 
controllers have been injured said officials with the federal 
aviation administration and the union the national air traffic 
control association but faa spokesman mort edelstein said theres 
a nationwide problem with broken chairs 
we bought 10000 of these chairs from 1985 to 1986 five 
percent to 9 percent are considered not usable today and about 20 
percent are considered broken but usable edelstein said 
the agency has had difficulty getting replacement parts for 
broken chairs he said they have to go to oklahoma city for 
the parts and theres a backlog of orders 
ron downen a union representative at the aurora center said 
there were at least 12 broken chairs among the 121 chairs he 
counted in the control room on a shift this week when 143 people 
were on duty the center employs about 400 controllers said faa 
spokesman mike ficocello 
not all the controllers on the shift were handling planes 
because of lunch breaks rest breaks and training sessions so all 
working controllers had chairs downen said 
but bad weather or computer troubles could require more 
controllers at radar screens at once threatening a chair shortage 
he said 
we need more chairs before the thunderstorm season hits 
said kevin christy another union area representative 
the faa believes the center has enough usable chairs said 
spokesman bob buckhorn in washington 
we do have a problem in maintenance and were expediting a 
program to ensure those broken chairs are either fixed or 
replaced buckhorn said anywhere we find a shortage of chairs 
were taking steps to correct that its not interfering with the 
operation of the center he said 
the chairs were designed to reduce fatigue and aid posture and 
were the best chairs available that met controllers requirements 
buckhorn said 
but christy said the chairs arent as sturdy as the ones they 
replaced 
they get hard use because theyre sat in 24 hours a day 
rocked back and forth rolled across the aisles christy said 
but the chairs werent built to last they dont even look sturdy 
the arms are falling off the wheels are getting stuck and the 
backs break off theyre comfortable but they replaced chairs we 
had years ago that were comfortable too and could stand a lot of 
abuse 
the faa has had trouble in the past filling vacancies at the 
center because it is one of the busiest in the air traffic control 
network but a program giving controllers at busier centers extra 
pay has largely eliminated the problem 
