<TEXT>
the united states will let americans travel to libya 
to help wipe out a deadly parasite that threatens africas 
livestock and wildlife un officials said wednesday 
in january president bush renewed sanctions against libya 
including a ban on american travel the measures date back to 
former president ronald reagan who accused libyas leader col 
moammar gadhafi of sponsoring terrorism 
earlier this year us officials denied requests by the united 
nations food and agriculture organization for permission to send 
american experts to libya and help rid the north african country of 
the screwworm fly 
however in march bush allowed us officials to sell libya 
sterile screwworms in an attempt to wipe out the parasite 
henryk jasiorowski fao assistant director general said the 
united states also has agreed to allow us technicians employed by 
international organizations to travel to libya but only on 
international passports 
the fly settles in wounds or tick bites and in a few days can 
kill its animal hosts by eating away at tissues humans with flesh 
wounds can also invite infestation it was first sighted in 
northern africa in july 1988 
another fao official bjorn sigurbjornsson said an american 
entomologist employed by the fao and the international atomic 
energy agency is working in libya this month 
this is very important because the knowhow is american 
jasiorowski said at a news briefing about the pest 
the united states became an expert on the pest after a 
devastating infestation of livestock in the american southwest 
entomologists developed a patented way of irradiating the flies to 
make them sterile and the parasite was wiped out in the united 
states by 1982 
under the strategy tens of millions of flies are sterilized at 
a facility in mexico then released from airplanes above an 
infested area matings yield no offspring and the insect dies out 
international experts have devised an 85 million twoyear plan 
that calls for the release of treated flies in libya starting in 
1991 a trial program is to begin this summer 
confirmed sightings of the pest have been limited to a swath 
across northern libya but experts say the infestation could 
spread particularly vulnerable they say are libyas neighbors 
tunisia and egypt 
in egypt the fly could move quickly down the nile river valley 
into central africa threatening livestock as well as exotic 
wildlife in central africa the experts said southern europe is 
also considered at risk 
sigurbjornsson said he thought egypt and tunisia helped persuade 
the united states to allow americans into libya us officials 
have traveled to both tunisia and egypt to aid inspection there he 
said 
after talks earlier this year washington was persuaded also to 
allow the american technology to be used in libya against the 
screwworm fly us officials only agreed after receiving 
assurances no resources would be given directly to the libyan 
government 
experts say libyan inspection has so far helped prevent the pest 
from spreading beyond its present area two relatively miled 
winters have also helped contain the fly 
although fao officials praised us collaboration in the effort 
sources have said the timetable for fullscale eradication could 
have been much sooner if it werent for obstacles posed by the us 
sanctions 
the flys appearance in libya was its debut outside the western 
hemisphere it was believed to have entered libya on an infected 
animal probably from latin america 
</TEXT>
