<DOCNO> AP900418-0164 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
nations will have to impose stronger controls on 
ozonedestroying chemicals if the atmosphere is to be made safe for 
ozone again within the next century a new study suggests 
even if all emissions were stopped in the year 2000 levels of 
ozonedepleting chlorine in the atmosphere would not drop to 
relatively benign levels until about the year 2070 the study says 
the work is presented in thursdays issue of the british journal 
nature by michael prather and robert watson of the national 
aeronautics and space administration 
scientists are concerned about destruction of ozone at high 
altitudes because that ozone layer shields earth from solar rays 
that can cause skin cancer 
the united states and other nations have signed a 1987 
agreement called the montreal protocol in which they pledged to 
cut production of some ozonedestroying chemicals in half by the 
end of this decade 
since then representatives of 81 countries have called for an 
end to production and use of ozonedestroying chlorofluorocarbons 
by the year 2000 
the new study considered not only the compounds covered by the 
montreal protocol but also other ozonedepleting compounds 
including carbon tetrachloride and methyl chloroform it estimated 
how long it would take under various degrees of regulation of the 
compounds to lower the atmospheric concentration of chlorine from 
more than 3 parts per billion today to 2 parts per billion 
the lower figure was the concentration in the late 1970s when 
scientists first noticed the ozone hole an area over 
antarctica in which a substantial amount of ozone disappears every 
year 
the study found that if emissions were cut to half of their 1985 
levels at the end of the year 2000 atmospheric chlorine 
concentrations would dip only slightly from a starting level of 
just under 5 parts per billion and then rise above 53 parts per 
billion by the year 2100 
if emissions were eliminated in the year 2000 chlorine 
concentrations would reach the 2 parts per billion target in the 
year 2073 researchers said but the target might be difficult or 
impossible to reach by the year 2100 if chlorinebearing 
substitutes for chlorofluorocarbons were used indefinitely 
researchers said 
similarly a 90 percent reduction in emissions in the year 2000 
would delay reaching the target until 2175 researchers said 
guy brasseur director of the atmospheric chemistry division at 
the national center for atmospheric research in boulder colo 
called the study important 
it shows he says that at the present time we havent solved 
the problem 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
