the first detector of plastic explosives to be 
installed by us officials in a foreign airport is to be set up at 
londons gatwick airport in a few weeks a spokesman for the 
company that built it said wednesday 
the federal aviation administration announced that it signed an 
agreement with the british airports authority for the thermal 
neutron analysis or tna unit in the public area of the airport 
for use by us and other airlines 
the faas decision to use the machines was prompted by the 
bombing of pan am flight 103 in december 1988 over lockerbie 
scotland that killed 270 people 
other neutron analysis units have been installed at john f 
kennedy airport in new york and at miamis international airport 
but both have been put in baggage areas and handle luggage of only 
one carrier 
the faa said baggage destined for the united states aboard us 
carriers will be given first priority for the london machine the 
next prioirty will be other planes bound for the united states 
the machine has been ready and boxed for several weeks said 
hadi bozorgmanesh vice president of science applications 
international corp of california the only manufacturer 
bozorgmanish said in a telephone interview that space for the 
machine is ready at gatwick 
the faa has ordered us airlines to pay for and install nuetron 
analysis units or similar machines at highrisk airports they use 
around the world the london machine however will be operated by 
the airport rather than an airline 
faa administrator james b busey has said he has been frustrated 
by difficulties with negotiations to install the devices in 
airports the agency is negotiating to put the machines in airports 
in frankfurt west germany where flight 103 originated and 
