<TEXT>
the united states in february recorded its 
smallest trade deficit in more than six years a 649 billion 
imbalance that reflected a sharp drop in oil imports the 
government reported wednesday 
the bush administration hailed the dramatic narrowing of the 
deficit but later in the day released a new forecast which 
pessimistically predicted that further trade improvements this year 
were likely to be at best very modest 
the administrations trade forecast required by congress said 
that any further narrowing of the trade deficit this year is likely 
to be much smaller than in the past two years and that a modest 
widening of the deficit could not be ruled out 
the commerce department said februarys trade gap was down 30 
percent from a 932 billion january deficit it was the best trade 
showing since december 1983 when the deficit was 568 billion 
imports fell by 76 percent to 3812 billion while us 
exports totaled 3163 billion a modest 1 percent decline from an 
alltime high for exports set in january 
michael boskin president bushs chief economic adviser called 
the trade figure very good news indeed while cautioning that 
we cant tell yet the extent to which it is a temporary or 
permanent phenomenon 
some private economists remained pessimistic contending that 
februarys good showing came primarily from a huge 20 percent drop 
in oil imports thats not likely to be sustained 
with us domestic oil production at 25year lows many 
economists look for americas dependence on foreign oil to continue 
rising thus holding back improvements in the trade deficit 
last years trade deficit totaled 109 billion and many analysts 
are looking for the figure to deteriorate this year reflecting a 
higher oil bill and weaker export growth because of the strength of 
the us dollar 
a stronger dollar makes us goods less competitive in overseas 
markets 
its nice to have a low number for february but it would 
certainly be a mistake to conclude that our competitiveness 
problems have disappeared and everything is now terrific for us on 
international markets said lawrence chimerine senior economic 
adviser at the wefa group an economic consulting company in bala 
cynwyd pa 
but bruce steinberg senior economist at merrill lynch said he 
believed the trade deficit would shrink further this year falling 
below 100 billion for the first time since 1983 
he said americas trade fortunes were being helped by strong 
demand in western europe the primary market for us exports 
while the trade balance with japan worsened in february rising 
to 312 billion the united states ran a 1 billion trade surplus 
with western europe 
we have gone from running big trade deficits with western 
europe to being in rough balance and everything is in place to 
start running big surpluses steinberg said 
the administrations trade outlook held out some hope that the 
dramatic changes occurring in eastern europe would narrow trade 
differences at least in europe 
the report said that the unification of west and east germany 
should act to lower west germanys huge trade surplus because the 
united country will need to import more from abroad to meet 
increased demand 
the deficit with japan which accounted for half of februarys 
total imbalance is coming as the bush administration applies heavy 
pressure on the government of prime minister toshiki kaifu to open 
japanese markets to more american products 
regardless of their view about future trade prospects 
economists agreed that februarys improvement would significantly 
boost overall economic growth for the first three months of the 
year 
steinberg predicted that the overall economy as measured by the 
gross national product expanded at an annual rate of between 25 
percent to 3 percent with more than 1 percentage point of that 
gain coming from a smaller trade deficit 
in the final three months of 1989 the gnp grew at a sluggish 
11 percent rate 
oil imports which surged by 44 percent in january fell in 
february by 20 percent to 471 billion reflecting a drop in the 
price per barrel and the number of barrels imported 
the big swing in both months was weather related with cold 
december temperatures pushing up demand and an unusually warm 
january cutting back on oil imports in february 
in addition to the drop in oil shipments imports of consumer 
appliances and other durable goods fell by 75 percent while 
imports of clothing and other consumer nondurable goods dropped by 
10 percent primarily reflecting sluggish us demand analysts 
said 
however imports of foreign cars were up by 25 percent to 256 
billion in february 
on the export side there were small declines in a variety of 
areas but these were offset by a doubling in sales of aircraft 
which climbed to 227 billion reflecting a spurt in shipments by 
the seattlebased boeing co which was idled by a strike late last 
year 
