an international ban on trade in ivory 
has sent prices plummeting on most traditional markets the world 
conservation union said wednesday 
in several countries shrinking demand also has led to reduced 
poaching a study by the group said poaching was blamed as a major 
factor in reducing africas elephant population from 13 million to 
about 610000 in the past 15 years 
the treaty to protect the dwindling herds took effect jan 18 
following a 103nation meeting in october of members of the 
convention on trade in endangered species 
it bans trade in ivory and all other elephant products five 
southern african nations which regularly cull their elephant 
populations botswana malawi south africa zambia and zimbabwe 
filed for exemptions china has declared it will continue to import 
the tusks 
the world conservation union study says ivory prices in africa 
europe and africa fell significantly although they rose somewhat in 
japan where high internal demand remains 
the study cautioned however that with stockpiles rising 
because of natural mortality and confiscations there is growing 
danger that much of this ivory will enter trade through nations 
that did not sign the treaty 
it said the large quantities of stockpiled ivory at least 250 
tons in africa and another 580 tons in consumer countries thus 
may foster new markets which will be difficult if not impossible 
to control 
