<TEXT>
the cleanup of environmentally 
sensitive areas of prince william sound fouled by the exxon valdez 
oil spill may resume as early as friday exxon corp and government 
officials said wednesday 
a boat carrying exxons first 1990 cleanup crew will be ready to 
begin work then said andy teal coordinator of exxons shoreline 
cleanup assessment team 
the crew may initially begin cleaning sea bird rookeries and 
areas where seals and sea lions congregate teal said in order to 
minimize disrupting nesting activities in may 
the need to clean those sites is not yet certain however he 
said the first sites to be cleaned will not be determined until the 
federal coordinator on the scene gives the goahead 
the coordinator rear adm david ciancaglini is expected to 
begin approving site cleanup recommendations soon said coast guard 
spokesman ernest del bueno 
the general cleanup of remaining oiled shorelines in prince 
william sound and the gulf of alaska begins may 1 exxon officials 
said 
the 1989 cleanup was halted sept 15 in anticipation of winter 
hundreds of miles of shoreline in prince william sound were 
covered with an oily goo when the tanker exxon valdez ran aground 
on a charted reef on march 24 1989 spilling nearly 11 million 
gallons of north slope crude oil countless fish otters other 
mammals and sea birds were killed 
exxon says it spent more than 2 billion in last years cleanup 
hiring more than 10000 workers and leasing more than 1000 boats 
for the operation the company says it plans a greatly reduced 
cleanup this year 
a technical advisory group composed of representatives of the 
coast guard the national oceanic and atmospheric administration 
the alaska department of environmental conservation and exxon has 
been meeting for a week to determine cleanup methods for about 600 
shoreline sites 
recommendations include simply picking up tarladen mats coating 
rocky shorelines and raking shoveling and using backhoes or other 
equipment to remove deepseated oil from rocks and soil 
proposals also include spraying fertilizer or chemicals on 
beaches to break down the remaining oil 
certain cleanup methods have created some controversy and state 
regulators have not yet said whether they will approve the use of 
fertilizers on shorelines or the introduction of large machinery 
exxon and a subsidiary exxon shipping co are scheduled to go 
on trial in us district court in anchorage on june 18 on two 
