<TEXT>
it may be true that it never rains on investors 
in money market mutual funds but every now and then in moneyfund 
land the rumble of distant thunder can be heard 
that message was driven home afresh a few days ago with the news 
that a prominent firm that manages a group of funds had dipped into 
its own pocket to protect its money fund against the threat of a 
loss 
t rowe price associates of baltimore which runs a 28 
billionplus stable of investments that includes 30 mutual funds 
said it had bought 646 million in securities of mortgage amp realty 
trust from portfolios it manages 
the market price of mamprts commercial paper or shortterm ious 
appeared ready to suffer a drop after the real estate investment 
trust filed for protection under chapter 11 of the federal 
bankruptcy law 
though t rowe price said it hopes and expects mamprt eventually 
to pay everything it owes on the paper the firm acted to stave off 
even the possibility of a small and temporary dip in the net asset 
value of its prime reserve fund and unspecified other pools of 
money 
price wasnt the only fund manager caught in that bind erick 
kanter a spokesman for the investment company institute a trade 
group said there were about half a dozen in all but declined 
to identify any of the others 
in no case apparently did money fund shareholders lose any 
money since the fund sponsors followed a precedent that is fast 
becoming the customary practice in cases like this 
when a fund is sitting on an investment that is losing market 
value because of a drop in the issuers credit standing it can be 
made whole through the sale of that security to the separate 
entity with different owners that sponsors the fund 
still the fact remains that fund managers typically are under 
no legal obligation to do this and conceivably could find 
themselves unable to take such action in some future instance 
involving large multiple defaults 
money funds however safe their records may be remain 
securities subject to at least theoretical risks without any 
backing from federal deposit insurance or any other government 
guarantee 
but that basic disclaimer doesnt answer the question of what 
further responsibilities if any should fall on the industry as in 
continues the growth that has brought it nearly 400 billion in 
assets in just two decades of existence 
right now the chief response of many fund advisers seems to 
have been to upgrade the safety of their holdings especially in 
commercial paper where they are already forbidden to venture 
beyond issuers with high credit ratings 
from the point of view of moneyfund investors and of a 
financial system in which the funds play an increasingly important 
role is that enough 
even the highest rating is no absolute assurance of safety in an 
investment like commercial paper which normally is not secured by 
any particular asset of the corporation that issues it 
says james grant financial newsletter publisher and frequent 
critic of many credit practices of recent years now that the 
corporate credit risk has been positively identified in the 
junkbond market perhaps it is time to look somewhere else for 
it 
at the same time officials in the industry dismiss recurrent 
conjecture that they might have set up or be planning to create 
some unpublicized rainyday reserve to help cope with any future 
crisis 
perhaps some day money funds will have a backup system analagous 
to deposit insurance in banking but it could prove a painful error 
for investors to suppose that any such thing exists today 
