<DOCNO> AP900418-0202 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
corporate management is maturing and it 
probably means a more competitive industrial america in the 1990s 
it is very good news says professor eugene jennings 
jennings assessment is based on research of corporate and 
managerial data an endeavor now into its fifth decade making it 
the longest existing and continuing study of business by the same 
researcher 
it began in the 1950s with the curiosity of a young man seeking 
to make his mark in university circles it continues with the same 
intensity but the man is now a professor emeritus adviser to 
corporate chairmen and a prolific author 
in writing the manuscript for a new book to be called 
chiefs jennings professor emeritus of management at michigan 
state universitys graduate school of business found that american 
corporate management now blends some of the best of the new ideas 
with those proven in the past 
it leads him to conclude industrial america is probably 
better positioned for competition now than ever before judging 
from the qualities of chiefs selected in the past decade 
the comparisons of various measurements of corporate chiefs are 
consistent each tending to support the other 
first jennings compared the ratios of what he calls natives and 
immigrants in his lexicon a native is a chief who grew up within 
the company and an immigrant is one appointed from outside the 
business 
in pre1960s days corporations were inflexible chiefs almost 
always were named from within the company in the 1960s the ratio 
became 5050 meaning just as many were brought into the company as 
were nurtured within 
in the 1980s however the ratios shifted back to a middle 
position now three times as many chief executives are appointed 
from within as from without it indicates says jennings that 
boards are being more selective in their search for the best no 
longer are they blind to the possibilities of outsiders but they 
also recognize the importance of promoting from within 
he made another comparison in pre1960s there was no such 
thing as an early arrival or a person appointed chief executive at 
age 49 or younger in the 1960s 40 percent were early arrivals 
now it is down to 25 percent 
the blend of old and new continues in another test in the 
prewatershed days of the 1960s socalled late arrivals age 58 or 
older made up 30 percent of appointments in the 1960s late 
arrivals dropped out of sight companies wanted young blood but in 
the 1980s the percentage rose to 21 percent 
at this point says jennings some people might think of the 
1960s as irresponsible at any rate he said they had very poor 
screening of the top executives the antiestablishment attitude 
it seems rose to the very top 
a fourth test underscored the consistency of old to new to 
middle ground 
in prewatershed days almost nobody was named chief executive 
who didnt have his hands on the product such as in sales and 
manufacturing these people are often said to have online 
experience 
in the 1960s that old way changed more than 50 percent were 
named who had no hands on experience but in the 1980s screening 
committees rediscovered the old ways the percentage without hands 
on experience dropped to 27 percent 
still another test showed similar results migrant chiefs or 
chairmen appointed from outside were uncommon before the 1960s 
but all at least had experience within the industry 
in the 1960s however only a slim majority of those named chief 
had experience within the same industry but that too changed in 
the 1980s the vast majority of migrants had experience within the 
particular industry 
same trend with another test this one age before the 1960s it 
took 33 years to produce a chief in the decade of the 1960s it 
took only 215 years then in the 1980s it rose to 26 years as 
industry opted for more experience 
to jennings it means that today american industry wants and is 
getting seasoned and surefooted executives preferring them to 
the younger vital exhuberant types 
in a sense he says screening committees are seeking better 
corporate health just as all america does when it seeks better 
nutrition and care in handling drugs and arteryclogging foods 
business is choosing good blood over fresh blood he says 
industry he says is getting a better balance of proteins and 
carbohydrates rather than fresh blood hyped with vitamins 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

