<TEXT>
in the dim light of a supersecure 
command bunker army lt col john w wilson paced chin on chest 
listening to an intelligence report on a soviet submarine off the 
california coast 
an instant later as he glanced up at an illuminated global 
chessboard of us and sviet military forces wilson stopped 
short a voice near him cried bsts alert an earlywarning 
satellite was signaling the launch of a nuclear missile 
wilson had the comfort of knowing this was only a war game 
simulation but voices in the control center carried a serious tone 
from the moment a us surveillance plane over the pacific reported 
spotting a missile booster surging toward the surface 
for wilson it was time to start thinking about doomsday and how 
to escape 
he sent word to the white house we have a detected launch off 
the west coast 
then nearly as abruptly as the attack had begun it was 
over minutes after the count of incoming soviet missiles reached 
15 and before the warheads could hit their targets in the 
southwestern united states all were destroyed in a space and 
landbased rocket barrage orchestrated from wilsons bunker 
the crisis was a computersimulated nuclear attack it was 
not the allout assault that america has spent trillions of dollars 
trying to deter throughout the cold war but a smallscale launch 
by a rogue soviet submarine commander 
the scenario played out for reporters recently at the armys 
strategic defense command dramatizes the new rationale being 
promoted by the bush administration for investing billions in a 
star wars missile defense at a time when even the pentagon 
acknowledges that the threat of world war iii is the lowest in 40 
years 
instead of the impregnable worldwide shield against a massive 
wave of soviet missiles as originally envisioned by ronald reagan 
seven years ago promoters of the strategic defense initiative say 
a more modest defense is needed one that still would put weapons 
in space at a cost of about 55 billion but would be capable of 
knocking out only half of the soviets main intercontinental 
ballistic missile force 
the new rationale also stresses a need to protect against an 
accidental or unauthorized soviet launch or a limited missile 
attack by a third world country 
gone is reagans talk of making nuclear weapons impotent and 
obsolete the aim now is to improve the traditional role of 
offensive nuclear forces as a deterrent to war by making the odds 
of a successful first strike even more uncertain 
gone at least for the remainder of this century are ideas of 
using exotic and futuristic weaponry such as the xray laser and 
particle beam weapon that originally gave sdi the star wars 
nickname the new emphasis is on more downtoearth rapidly 
maturing technology such as kineticenergy warheads that kill 
their targets in space by ramming them at high speed 
gone too is much of the interest in congress for financing the 
project last year for the first time the sdi budget was lower 
than in the year before today its an easy target of politicians 
looking to harvest a postcold war peace dividend 
sdi is public enemy no 1 on capitol hill sen john warner 
rva said recently 
says rep charles bennett dfla who supports a scaleddown 
sdi research budget but not deployment congress hasnt voted to 
produce it and probably never will 
bush has told the pentagon he wants to be able to decide by 1992 
whether to deploy a star wars defense but he probably wont get 
the chance by then officials and scientists working on the project 
say theyll need a healthy increase in funds well above what 
congress seems likely to grant next year and in 1992 to lay a 
sound technical foundation on which bush could base his decision 
lt gen robert d hammond commander of the strategic defense 
command that handles about onethird of the star wars research 
told reporters recently that he believed bush could meet his target 
date for a deployment decision only if you have good growth in 
financing beyond the 38 billion authorized for this year 
bush has requested a 1 billion increase for next year but it 
appears unlikely hell get anything close to that he and the 
pentagon may have to live with less 
from the start more than seven years and 19 billion ago the 
project was designed as a longterm effort with little prospect 
for payoff before the turn of the century but political pressure 
to show results grew as policymakers wondered can it work is it 
affordable will the soviets find a way around it 
all three are still open questions 
the main pieces of a star wars system as currently envisioned 
are sensors to detect and track enemy missiles from their launch 
silos land and spacebased rockets to attack the missiles in 
flight and computers to manage the battle 
of those three elements the computer technology is perhaps the 
most problematic 
at the strategic defense command in hunstville where wilson and 
his team of specialists test their responses to simulated nuclear 
attacks engineers are still experimenting with computer programs 
that would be used to orchestrate a star wars response to a real 
attack 
lawrence tubbs acting chief of battle management at the 
strategic defense command said the key questions about the 
computer software are can it be adequately tested and would it 
work 
some scientists say the answer to both is no 
the problem of developing trustworthy software for the sdi is 
not a problem that will be solved in our lifetimes or those of our 
children the computer professionals for social responsibility 
wrote in an open letter to congress on feb 16 
the scientists group urged the abandonment of sdi arguing that 
a single error in the systems software could cause a complete 
system failure under unpredictable circumstances 
it appears unlikely star wars will be killed any time soon if 
only because of its economic lure about 28000 people are working 
on the project at defense contractors national laboratories 
universities and military installations in every state in the 
nation and in five foreign countries 
two aerospace companies boeing co and lockheed corp together 
have taken in 22 billion in star wars contracts over the life of 
the program according to pentagon figures that is more than 10 
percent of all star wars spending altogether more than 1000 
military contractors have a piece of star wars action 
the projects supporters say the american public will support 
more research if they get the message that the goal of ballistic 
missile defense is attainable 
lt gen george monahan director of the sdi project 
acknowledged in testimony to a house panel april 4 that much more 
work was needed to put the star war pieces together but he said 
many scientific question marks have been erased 
there is no doubt in my mind that the technology is here 
sufficient to develop and deploy such a system he said 
</TEXT>
