<TEXT>
it was one of the most widely quoted oneliners 
in wall streets insider trading scandal your bunny has a good 
nose but there was nothing funny about it for robert freeman 
the former head of arbitrage for goldman sachs amp co was 
ordered tuesday to serve four months in prison and pay a 1 million 
fine for trading securities after hearing the comment which helped 
him conclude that a takeover deal was in trouble 
us district judge pierre leval said he imposed a prison term 
to send a message to wall street that insider trading and other 
whitecollar crime cannot be treated lightly 
these practices seriously undermine the integrity of the 
marketplace he said later adding it is perhaps one of the 
consequences of enormous power and wealth that there are 
downsides 
leva sentenced freeman to one year in prison but suspended the 
last eight months of the term the judge said he rejected a lengthy 
term because freeman was shown to be a good man who was chastened 
by his crime freeman faced a maximum of five years 
the sentence capped one of the longest and most contentious 
episodes in the governments crackdown on insider trading stemming 
from the confessions of former stock speculator ivan f boesky 
freeman 47 pleaded guilty last august to one count of mail 
fraud for using illegally obtained inside information to trade 
securities in connection with the proposed takeover of beatrice 
cos by kohlberg kravis roberts amp co 
he admitted getting information from former kidder peabody amp 
co investment banker martin siegel who has pleaded guilty to two 
counts and is awaiting sentencing kidder represented kkr in the 
proposed takeover 
the case turned on a comment made by siegel after freeman called 
him on jan 8 1986 to try to confirm rumors that the beatrice 
takeover was in jeopardy 
freeman told siegel he had heard about problems in the deal from 
a prominent new york stock exchange trader bernard bunny 
lasker siegel responded your bunny has a good nose freeman 
said in an account of the episode 
after taking the call freeman reduced goldmans stake in 
beatrice he admitted to a felony crime for the action but defense 
lawyers said it did not merit prison the government had requested 
prison time 
mr freeman is a good man who made a mistake that he has 
admitted for which he has been punished extraordinarily defense 
attorney paul curran said citing the agony that mr freeman and 
his family had to endure beginning with his arrest on false charges 
three years ago 
freeman was arrested in february 1987 along with two other wall 
street executives on charges the us attorneys office in 
manhattan called the tip of the iceberg 
but the government dropped the original indictments and last 
year called off its investigation of the two others timothy tabor 
and richard wigton wigton was arrested on his trading floor and 
hauled away in handcuffs the nature of the arrests and their 
disposition provoked outrage on wall street 
leval said the conversation with siegel who implicated freeman 
after he was linked to insider trading by boesky was illegal and 
deserved prison 
although the answer was couched in veiled language it 
constituted the illegal transaction of inside information leval 
said there is no question he knew full well he was breaking 
the law 
the 1 million fine was about twice the trading loss avoided by 
goldman freeman and his clients by selling the beatrice holdings 
the maximum penalty under the law leval said freeman has 30 days 
to pay 
freeman who lives in the new york suburb of rye also was 
placed on two years probation and ordered to serve 300 hours of 
community service freeman asked to serve his sentence in a 
minimumsecurity prison camp in pensacola fla he must surrender 
to the government june 19 
