<TEXT>
the chicago mercantile exchange hopes its newly 
proposed curbs on dualtrading will convince federal regulators to 
stop considering more drastic bans 
members of the exchange voted tuesday to approve a 
managementbacked plan to ban the controversial practice for 
twothirds of the mercs trading volume 
the merc said 76 percent of the 1561 ballots cast favored the 
restrictions which were drawn up by an exchange committee and 
approved recently by board of governors the exchange has 2500 
active members 
dualtrading is the longstanding practice of floor brokers 
trading for their own accounts and for customers 
a government probe of the merc and the chicago board of trade 
zeroed in on dualtrading and other practices as key factors in 
trader abuse 
despite the potential for abuse the merc and the board of trade 
argue that dualtrading brings an added level of liquidity to the 
market helping guarantee that at any moment someone wanting to 
sell or buy a contract will find someone with whom to do business 
the proposal approved by merc members would ban dualtrading in 
contracts that have a proven record of liquidity 
contracts in which there isnt much business usually those for 
delivery in distant months still would permit dualtrading 
the lightly traded contracts also are more easily monitored for 
abuses said merc spokesman andrew yemma 
the commoditiy futures trading commission has proposed a trial 
reform in which dualtrading would be banned for all delivery 
months for one financial future and one agricultural commodity 
the merc said it will ask the cftc to approve the exchanges 
proposal in lieu of the agencys pilot program 
the cftc is expected to make a final determination late in the 
summer 
congress also is considering dualtrading restrictions that 
would be potentially more severe than those proposed by the merc 
the mercs proposed restrictions were recommended by a committee 
that reviewed trading practices in light of the government 
investigation in which 48 people mostly traders have been 
indicted 
even before the investigation was revealed last year the merc 
banned dualtrading in 1987 for 90 percent of the trades in its 
standard amp poors 500 stockindex futures pit 
there was a feeling among members in the pit that there were 
abuses of dualtrading that needed to be addressed said yemma 
the board of trade also believes the cftc proposal goes too far 
said cbot spokesman michael oconnell 
there currently are no restrictions on dualtrading at the board 
of trade and officials there want to keep it that way oconnell 
said dualtrading accounts for a great source of market 
liquidity he said 
</TEXT>
