<TEXT>
donaldson lufkin amp jenrette securities corp 
agreed to pay back 56 million to customers for stock sold in 
partial tender offers without prior client approval federal 
officials said 
the new yorkbased securities firm and a managing director 
michael dreitlein agreed to settle without admitting or denying 
wrongdoing an administrative action alleging they violated 
securities and exchange commission antifraud and recordkeeping 
rules the settlement was disclosed tuesday 
the action brought by the secs new york regional office 
accused donaldson lufkin amp jenrettes pershing division of making 
43 million in tender offer profits from the unauthorized and 
undisclosed sale of shares from customer accounts 
a tender offer is an offer to buy a corporations shares often 
as a means of acquiring the concern usually at a premium price 
according to the sec the pershing division thenheaded by 
dreitlein tendered shares belonging to customers who had not given 
any instructions to do so the shares were later replaced usually 
with stock bought at a lower price after the tender offer dlj kept 
any profits from the difference between the sale and repurchase 
price 
the alleged activity known as overtendering took place between 
january 1982 and april 1988 the sec said 
securities transactions are predicated on trust dlj misued 
that trust when it confiscated customers securities for its 
benefit said martin a kuperberg the secs associate regional 
administrator in new york 
kathryn ashbaugh brokerdealer enforcement branch chief in new 
york explained that while the misappropriated securities were 
replaced with no quantifiable loss to customers the increased 
number of shares dlj sold in 104 partial tender offers effectively 
dilluted the number shareholders could sell to the acquiring 
company 
in a partial tender offer the acquirer isnt seeking 100 
percent of the corporations stock and therefore not every 
shareholder can sell stock 
as part of the settlement with the sec dlj agreed to pay 43 
million plus interest for a total of 56 million to customers 
whose shares were used in the overtendering 
dreitlein consented to a 45day suspension from any 
secregulated securities operations and an 18month ban from 
supervising any department that handles partial tender offers 
these are practices that date to the early and mid 1980s 
said catherine conroy a spokeswoman for the jersey city 
njbased pershing division she noted that dlj has instituted 
several steps to upgrade and strengthen the division and this 
brings the matter to a satisfactory close 
</TEXT>
