the failure of the 22 billion silverado banking 
savings and loan was brought on by fraud and abuse not a 
struggling colorado economy according to federal documents 
documents obtained by the denver post through the federal 
freedom of information act said the failed denver thrift repeatedly 
violated federal banking laws the paper said in a copyright report 
in todays editions 
regulators said that the december 1988 failure resulted from 
massive amounts of poorly underwritten loans imprudent loan 
concentrations and excessive compensation to senior 
management 
authorities had alleged that the thrift paid its top executives 
millions of dollars showed false profits hid loan problems and 
schemed to deceive regulators 
silverado has suffered due to violations of laws rules and 
regulations the depressed condition of colorados economy has 
served to exacerbate the losses incurred but it is not the reason 
for silverados insolvency the regulators said 
officials said the situation illustrates the nations 325 
billion thrift crisis 
there is a similarity that has emerged at all these failed 
thrifts said tony adamski chief of the fbis financial crime 
unit in washington in each case rules and good management were 
simply abrogated 
reports show that silverados troubles began in 1980 just a year 
after chairman michael wise took control and changed its name from 
mile high savings 
regulators warned then of increasing problem loans conflicts of 
interest regarding an insider loan and deficiencies in internal 
control 
the next year regulators said silverado was in danger of 
falling below minimum required levels of capital then from 1983 to 
1985 silverado doubled in size each year pouring loans into real 
estate projects seemingly without regard for the quality of the 
loans regulators said 
during that time the thrifts apparent profits almost entirely 
came from fees generated from making loans not the loans 
themselves regulators said 
typically such a reliance on fee income is a red flag for 
regulators said ronn carr of the federal office of thrift 
supervision in topeka kan it indicates there isnt an ongoing 
source of income from loans 
in 1985 foreclosures rose 10 times to 177 million and 
nonperforming loans quadrupled to 88 million regulators said but 
instead of setting aside reserves which would have produced a 20 
million loss that year silverado reported an 8 million profit 
in 1986 worried regulators set limits on silverados expansion 
other reports then followed until the failure in 1988 of 
imprudent business practices and even attempts to hide 
escalating troubles in its loan portfolio the documents said 
in a cashraising effort silverado issued 45 million in 
silverado stock to its senior officers telling regulators they 
bought it the reports said in fact silverado accountants just 
issued the stock free of charge and recorded the purchases as 
future pay the reports said 
silverado also lumped all bad loans and real estate it acquired 
through foreclosure into a 11 billion pool of major assets and 
then reported to regulators the loan pool was a health asset 
reports said 
the effect was to manipulate financial statements to report a 
more favorable condition regulators said in the documents 
when federal marshals moved in in 1988 losses had reached 1 
billion officials said 
