<TEXT>
with lightning speed the norton co received a 
weapon today to help fight a hostile takeover bid from a british 
firm 
gov michael s dukakis signed a bill this morning designed to 
stall a proxy fight for control over nortons board of directors 
the bill which takes effect immediately was signed in worcester 
the home of norton 
the measure sped through the senate and house on voice votes 
tuesday hours after a legislative committee endorsed the bill 
we must do all we can to protect our best corporate citizens 
and their workers and families from having their livelihoods wiped 
out dukakis said in a statement this bill gives companies a 
welldeserved fighting chance against hostile raiders 
john nelson the chairman of norton told an enthusiastic crowd 
of workers that the company will continue to fight to remain 
independent 
norton faces a proxy fight at its annual shareholders meeting 
currently scheduled for april 26 but norton is asking a federal 
appeals court to allow the company to delay the showdown until june 
26 so executives have more time to plan a defense strategy 
norton last month rejected a 16 billion 75ashare offer 
from btr but the british conglomerate says it will try to take 
control of nortons board at the shareholders meeting 
the new bill attempts to stall that strategy by requiring 
massachusetts companies to elect their boards of directors over 
staggered terms a company however could opt out of the 
requirement 
under the bill only onethird of the directors would be elected 
at a time which means btr would have to wait at least a year 
before it could place a majority of directors on the board 
currently a twothirds vote by shareholders is needed for a 
company to change to a staggered board 
the united shareholders association based in washington issued 
a statement saying the bill would strip the right of shareholders 
in massachusetts companies of their ability to vote on the board of 
directors annually 
state sen lois pines the committee cochairman acknowledged 
that norton would have trouble shifting to staggered board terms 
under current law because approximately 70 percent of its 
shareholders are big institutional investors 
but she insisted the bill protects shareholder interests 
it is important for a company that has served the community 
like norton has to have the opportunity to make its own judgments 
as to how to move forward within a reasonable amount of time 
pines said 
btr officials have vowed to continue their takeover bid even if 
blocked from wresting immediate control of the norton board 
with the collapse of the junk bond market and other sources of 
takeover financing bidders increasingly are turning to proxy 
fights which makes the new legislation necessary legislators said 
the bill also includes an amendment that would protect worker 
severance benefits if norton succeeds in defending itself but is 
forced to lay off employees 
the measure guarantees that the additional protection afforded 
to the board of directors would not be misused at the expense of 
workers who have most at stake pines said 
under current state law workers would receive severance 
benefits if the takeover fight is successful and a new owner takes 
control of the company but legislators said that if norton 
succeeds the battle could become quite costly and the company may 
have to cut its payroll 
the first round has gone to the workers said state sen 
john houston dworcester 
