<TEXT>
the european community on wednesday 
questioned the us commitment to international trade accords and 
cited a wide range of trade barriers 
in its fifth annual report on the matter the ec executive 
commission listed nearly 50 tariff and nontariff barriers to trade 
imposed by either washington or individual us states 
these included quantitative restrictions discriminatory public 
procurement policies unreasonable requirements for product 
testing labeling and certification as well as high customs fees 
export subsidies and tax barriers 
the ec report said these raise doubts whether the united 
states is sufficiently committed to the multilateral system which 
provides the main reference point for resolving disputes 
the report said the us must bring its trade legislation 
fully in conformity with multilaterally agreed rules it 
criticized washington for adopting trade laws that conflict with 
multilateral rules and for adopting clearly illegal trade 
measures 
contrary to popular belief in the united states the us 
government was guilty of the types of trade barriers it accuses 
other nations of erecting the report said 
in addition it accused us officials of tardiness in complying 
with rulings of the general agreement on tariffs and trade the 
genevabased international trade body 
the community is concerned by the extent to which nontariff 
barriers to its exports now seem to be more and more at the state 
rather than at the federal level the ec report said 
it blamed state regulations on taxation and on financial and 
professional services among others for creating serious 
handicaps to doing business in the us market 
