<DOCNO> AP900418-0245 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
many japanese have luxury cars diamonds and a 
penchant for some of the most expensive delicacies but find one 
coveted item out of reach land 
property prices have driven up business costs widened the 
wealth gap between landowners and landless and made home ownership 
impossible for the average japanese some banks offer 100year 
loans that can be passed down through generations a mortgage 
unheard of elsewhere 
land inflation has given japan 60 percent of the value of all 
real estate worldwide though it comprises 03 percent of the 
worlds land mass 
its not that theres an acute shortage of land on the island 
nation that became the economic miracle of the 20th century 
rather its a murky combination of bureaucracy tax shelters 
lobby interests and unbridled speculation that has made japan the 
planets priciest piece of real estate 
moreover the enormous value attached to japanese land has 
potential economic consequences that go far beyond the borders 
for example property prices affect the financial strength of 
speculators and other large investors who have used their land as 
collateral to buy stocks as much as half of japans phenomenal 
stock market growth of recent years is rooted in the value of 
japanese real estate 
some economists fear a fall in real estate values could 
devastate the stock market which already has dropped dramatically 
this year for other reasons and send financial shock waves around 
the world but others contend property prices must fall as part of 
a broader reform of japans economy 
in talks on changing business practices that have contributed to 
the longstanding us trade deficit with japan the government 
promised earlier this month to curb land inflation 
besides us pressure there also was recognition that drastic 
measures are needed to control real estate speculation and prevent 
the divide between property owners and nonowners from upsetting 
japans social stability said kisaburo ishii a construction 
ministry official involved in the talks 
land prices in tokyo soared 238 percent in 1987 and 653 
percent in 1988 before the increase slowed to less than 2 percent 
last year the national land agency reported 
nationwide however they jumped 17 percent after climbing 217 
percent in 1988 as speculative inflation spread to other major 
japanese cities last year in osaka japans secondbiggest city 
commercial land prices surged 439 percent and residential prices 
586 percent 
the worlds most expensive commercial property in central 
tokyos marunouchi and ginza business districts is valued at about 
23700 a square foot 
office space in tokyo rents for an average 191 a square foot 
vs 156 in london and 64 in new york with vacancy rates hovering 
around 02 percent its a landlords market 
after touting the my home dream for years newspapers now 
feature tales of families who scrimped for decades only to find 
even a modest home 90 minutes outside tokyo well out of reach 
an averagesize house of about 960 square feet about an hours 
commute from central tokyo costs 316000 inside tokyo prices 
shoot above 632000 for houses and about 378000 for smaller 
condominium apartments 
although mainstream wageearners now earn an average of 50000 
annually many are doomed to a renters life since banks generally 
will lend only four times an annual income for a conventional home 
mortgage 
competition for new homes in tokyos vast suburbs is so intense 
that hundreds apply for each opening many homes are sold by 
lottery before the foundations are laid 
some families giving up on ever owning a home instead are 
spending on cars travel and other luxuries 
nationwide an average of about 60 percent of all households own 
their homes in greater tokyo home to around 30 million of 
japans 122 million people only 40 percent do 
the government must deal with this problem said susumu 
ichihata senior managing director of the urban research institute 
in tokyo now that most japanese live in cities these problems 
could cause political unrest 
while rents on older apartments have been controlled for 
decades newcomers to the housing market face rents prohibitively 
high 
spacious westernstyle apartment rentals fetch 31409500 a 
month a 650squarefoot japanesestyle unit rents for about 820 
landlords customarily demand at least four months rent up front 
part refundable deposit but about two months rent in 
nonrefundable key money paid for the privilege of becoming a 
tenant 
renters find the home scramble a nightmare 
ive just returned to tokyo and we need to move to a bigger 
flat im really in a bind because theres no way we can afford to 
buy a home said tadao aoki a government aide who recently 
returned from a posting abroad 
most real estate purchases in tokyo today are by people with 
property to sell or to borrow against and by brokers buying and 
reselling land to profit from price increases 
real estate investment with its various writeoffs is seen as 
the easiest way for many high income earners and landowners to 
avoid high income and inheritance taxes 
the incentive becomes great for property brokers supported by 
bankers anxious not to miss a fastgrowing market to jack up 
prices 
banks accept the unrealized value of property as collateral 
and provide financing the same way a casino shucks out poker 
chips said tokunosuke hasegawa head of the research institute 
of construction and economy 
real estate lending is so lucrative that banks apparently have 
ignored repeated finance ministry warnings to cut back 
the government also is considering tax reforms aimed at shifting 
about 148200 acres of farmland and underutilized acreage in the 
tokyo metropolitan region to residential use 
farmland owners pay less than 00001 percent of the assessed 
value of their land in taxes compared with 7080 times that rate 
for residential land farmland also is virtually exempt from 
inheritance taxes which can rise as high as 80 percent of 
inherited assets 
tax reforms promised in japanus trade talks however face 
strong opposition from the powerful farm lobby and inertia among 
people accustomed to paying low taxes even if it means living 
without sewer lines 
although many japanese fear falling land prices could hurt the 
economy some economists contend that lower land prices would allow 
the japanese to build bigger better houses a development certain 
to boost the economy in the long run others say a propertymarket 
decline would squeeze out the worst of the speculators who have 
profited enormously from the cycle of land inflation 
this is a bubble economy and its time for the bubble to 
burst said hasegawa the real productive economy wont really 
be hurt land and people wont disappear but phony wealth will 
</TEXT>
