<TEXT>
oil prices continued to slide wednesday 
despite a vague call by a trio of opec heavyweights for cutting 
back on the the overproduction of crude oil 
on the new york mercantile exchange the nearterm crude 
contract settled at its lowest level in 16 months despite a 
statement from the oil ministers of saudi arabia kuwait and the 
united arab emirates urging production restraint 
its a fairly empty statement said nick antill an analyst 
at county natwest in london 
rumors swept the markets that kuwait and the united arab 
emirates members of the organization of petroleum exporting 
countries had privately agreed to slash their output 
but lucy mullins an analyst at barclays de zoete wedd in 
london said the market is taking all of this with a large pinch 
of salt 
if they wanted to reduce production they would probably 
have included it in the statement said pierre terzian editor of 
the parisbased newsletter petrostrategies 
moreover mullins said previous promises by persistent cheaters 
kuwait and the emirates to trim supply have not meant very much 
at all 
the two gulf countries have been pumping well above the quotas 
opec sets for each of its 13 members creating a world oil glut 
during the oftenweak second quarter of the year 
analysts estimate opec output at more than 24 million barrels a 
day exceeding the ceiling of 221 million barrels a day in effect 
for the first half of the year 
prices began plummeting sharply last week prompting hurried 
discussions among opec nations about whether to hold an emergency 
meeting 
no session has yet been called but a source close to the 
presidency of the cartel who demanded anonymity said it remains 
an option algerian mines minister sadek boussena is the current 
opec president 
