<TEXT>
house democrats unveiled their own 12 
trillion budget for next year on wednesday a plan that calls for 
8 billion less in military spending than president bush wants 
the package which the house budget committee plans to vote on 
thursday would also increase spending by 6 billion on programs 
that include child care nasa and aid to central america eastern 
europe and africa 
the proposal is the first detailed response by democratic 
leaders to the 1991 fiscal year budget bush requested in january 
at the time democrats complained bushs spending blueprint was not 
a serious effort to reduce the deficit and was too generous to the 
military at a time of lessening tensions with the soviet union 
the world has changed greatly said house speaker thomas s 
foley dwash who outlined highlights of the plan at a news 
conference with other top democrats the united states is 
obviously now in a position to look more intensively at the 
problems that lie within our own country 
house budget committee chairman leon panetta dcalif 
predicted approval by his democraticdominated panel he said the 
package reflects a transition from military confrontation to 
economic leadership from a cold war economy to a peacetime 
economy 
rep bill frenzel of minnesota ranking republican on the budget 
panel called the proposal a typical democratic budget without 
discipline gop lawmakers will vote aganst the democratic plan 
he said and continue pressing for talks between congress and the 
administration as the best way to close the budget gap 
the democratic proposal claims to trim the 1991 deficit by 36 
billion to 638 billion that would be just below the 64 billion 
target set by the grammrudman deficitreduction act which 
requires a balanced budget by 1993 fiscal 1991 begins oct 1 
the nonpartisan congressional budget office has said the 
administration is underestimating next years deficit by 70 
billion it expects the 1991 budget deficit to be 161 billion 
before budget reduction starts 
the democrats would slice 115 billion off the amount the 
military would need next year to stay abreast of inflation that 
would leave defense spending at 295 billion 8 billion less than 
bush wants 
they would shrink defense spending by 251 billion over the next 
five years about a 25 percent cut the democrats would spend 106 
billion of that on domestic programs and count 145 billion 
against the deficit 
the democrats would also cut next years military budget 
authority to 286 billion 30 billion below the total needed to 
keep up with inflation budget authority is the amount of spending 
an agency can enter into over a number of years the reduction is 
crucial because it would signal the start of a longrange decline 
in pentagon spending 
panettas plan would raise taxes by 139 billion the same 
amount bush proposed in january and collect an additional 56 
billion in new government fees 
the anticipated growth of medicare and other federal benefit 
programs would be slowed by 42 billion other savings would 
include delaying a federal pay raise for three months and improving 
the efficiency of tax collection 
the plan would also boost spending in several areas of science 
including nasa improve federal health efforts for children and 
increase expenditures for education road building and anticrime 
intiatives 
the congressional budget process was getting its formal start 
after weeks of closeddoor meetings among democratic budgetwriters 
and party leaders 
they spent much of their time fashioning a compromise on 
pentagon spending which represents onefourth of the budget 
between conservatives seeking levels similar to bushs request and 
liberals who wanted deeper cuts 
panetta and other leaders also had to sound out their members 
about two wellpublicized budget plans released by two top 
democrats earlier this year in the end they decided to ignore 
both proposals 
chairman dan rostenkowski dill of the taxwriting house ways 
and means committee had proposed saving 55 billion next year with 
a wide range of spending cuts and tax increases sen daniel 
patrick moynihan dny suggested cutting the social security 
payroll tax by 55 billion to intensify concerns about the budget 
deficit 
because these decisions had to be made congress again missed 
the april 15 legal deadline for completing its budget the 
requirement is routinely ignored year after year 
budget work is also going slowly in the senate where budget 
committee chairman james sasser dtenn is having trouble 
rounding up enough votes to move a spending plan out of his 
committee sasser favors cutting defense by 15 billion about 35 
billion more than panetta wants 
the budget resolution need only be passed by congress and does 
not need the presidents signature 
it is only a blueprint for spending and savings later bills 
will determine how the government spends its money and which taxes 
if any will be raised 
