apple computer inc said lower 
component costs success of new products and improved overseas 
sales helped it more than double earnings in the three months ended 
march 30 
the worlds no 2 personal computer maker said wednesday that 
net income for its fiscal second quarter was 1318 million or 
104 a share compared with 564 million or 44 cents a share a 
year earlier 
revenues rose 8 percent to 135 billion from 125 billion 
it was a very good report by any standard it was way at the 
far end of anyones expectations said steven ossad an analyst 
with montgomery securities in san francisco 
john sculley apples chairman and chief executive officer said 
the company was enjoying lower component costs and strong sales of 
computers introduced last year 
international sales also rose representing 47 percent of net 
sales during the latest quarter compared with 40 percent for the 
same period a year ago 
during the quarter the percentage of revenues coming from 
outside the united states reached an alltime high sculley said 
in a statement 
for the first six months of the fiscal year earnings rose 30 
percent to 2567 million or 2 a share from 1968 million or 
154 a share a year ago revenues rose 7 percent to 284 billion 
from 265 billion 
despite the quarters staggering performance the company 
was correct to be cautious in its forecast for the second half of 
1990 ossad said apple told analysts it was unlikely it would 
achieve 10 percent growth in the second half he added 
apple needs to increase the number of less expensive products 
particularly in light of the growing demand for computers among 
consumers and schools ossad said 
